# Functions are reusable pieces of code that perform a specific task. They allow you to break down your code into smaller, more manageable chunks, and they can be called multiple times throughout your program.
def my_function(): # This is the function definition. The name of the function is "my_function" and it takes no parameters.
    print("Hello") # This is the body of the function. It contains the code that will be executed when the function is called.
    print("Bye") # This is another line of code in the body of the function.

my_function() # This is how you call the function. When you call the function, the code inside the function will be executed. In this case, it will print "Hello" and "Bye" to the console.

#Tabs or spaces? Python's official style guide, PEP 8, recommends using 4 spaces per indentation level. This means that when you indent your code, you should use 4 spaces instead of a tab character. This helps to ensure that your code is consistent and easy to read across different editors and platforms.